    "narrative": "The Ghost Ride the WHIP lineup for 2026-04-09 leans heavily into situational speed and platoon advantages. **Jose Caballero** (77.16) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) headline our offensive output today. **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a massive 19% boost due to the matchup against V\u00e1squez, R, and his promotion to the #2 spot adds significant value for run scoring. Meanwhile, **Jose Caballero** remains a high-floor play despite his #8 slot; his 13% platoon edge and the opportunity to exploit Springs' slow delivery\u2014which heavily favors our pursuit of stolen bases\u2014make him an elite target to steal points in our scarcest category. **Giancarlo Stanton** (67.71) also provides a solid anchor in the middle of our order, utilizing a favorable 14% skill edge against the opposing starter to drive potential HR/RBI production.\n\nOur most difficult decision involved **Max Muncy** (61.96) versus our depth pieces. While **Max Muncy** secured the start over a crowded bench, the decision was marginal given the constraints. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** would have been a strong contender for a utility spot had he been confirmed in the lineup, as his speed profile is a core asset for this team, but his absence today makes the decision moot. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (51.61) remains in the lineup despite a 15% platoon penalty against Kay; however, we are banking on the 5% boost from wind-out conditions at the stadium to push his fly-ball production into our scoring range. Investors should keep an eye on **Tyler Soderstrom** (52.89) and **Zach McKinstry** (49.64), both of whom are operating near the efficiency floor; they are start-worthy, but represent the highest risk for underperformance if they fail to leverage their park factors. With **Corbin Carroll**, **Josh Naylor**, and **James Wood** sidelined by rest or scheduling, we are relying on our depth to maintain our category leads. Stay vigilant on the wind reports in Pasquantino\u2019s park, as any drop-off could turn his marginal start into a liability.",
